{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-b07d12ee80c37436", "type": "tool_result", "content": "1\tRethinking Speech Foundation Model Fine-tuning:\n2\tBetter SFT or Better Match?\n3\tWangjin Zhou1 , Yizhou Zhang1 , Yichi Wang1 , Tatsuya Kawahara1\n4\t1\n5\t\n6\tGraduate School of Informatics, Kyoto University, Kyoto, Japan\n7\t{zhou}@sap.ist.i.kyoto-u.ac.jp\n8\t\n9\tarXiv:2607.13864v1 [cs.SD] 15 Jul 2026\n10\t\n11\tAbstract\n12\tSupervised fine-tuning (SFT) is widely used to adapt selfsupervised speech representations to downstream classification\n13\ttasks. Small gains observed under a single pretrained checkpoint are often interpreted as method-level improvements, i.e.,\n14\ta higher attainable performance ceiling. We show that such\n15\tconclusions are not always reliable because SFT outcomes depend strongly on the specific pretrained instance. We conduct\n16\ta systematic study on 3 SUPERB classification tasks, evaluating 8 SFT variants across 9 pretrained checkpoints from\n17\twav2vec 2.0, HuBERT, and WavLM, with multi-seed repetitions on representative base-scale models. We find that the identity of the statistically indistinguishable top-group SFT recipe is\n18\toften checkpoint-dependent, with limited transferability across\n19\tpretrained instances. These findings suggest that many reported\n20\tdownstream gains reflect instance and seed dependent elicitation match, rather than universally improving the attainable performance ceiling.\n21\tIndex Terms: self-supervised learning, supervised fine-tuning,\n22\tspeech classification\n23\t\n24\t1. Introduction\n25\tSupervised fine-tuning (SFT) is a dominant paradigm for adapting self-supervised pretrained speech models [1, 2, 3] to downstream classification tasks [4, 5, 6]. In common practice, researchers compare SFT variants by downstream performance\n26\tand often treat small gains under a single pretrained checkpoint\n27\tas evidence that a recipe is “better,” i.e., achieving a higher attainable performance ceiling [7, 8].\n28\tThis practice implicitly assumes that the relative effectiveness of SFT methods is stable across pretrained model instances. In other words, a recipe that is “better” under one\n29\tpretrained checkpoint is expected to remain competitive under\n30\tother checkpoints of comparable capability [9, 10]. However,\n31\tthis assumption overlooks an important interaction in the adaptation process. Downstream performance is jointly shaped by\n32\tthe backbone architecture, the pretraining data, and the SFT\n33\trecipe [11]. Yet existing evaluations often consider these factors in isolation. In particular, the interaction between a recipe\n34\tand a specific pretrained instance is rarely examined [12, 13].\n35\tAs a result, even when the architecture and the model size are\n36\theld fixed, the apparent superiority of an SFT method may depend on which pretrained checkpoint it is applied to.\n37\tWe propose to view SFT as a process of capacity elicitation: fine-tuning attempts to activate and reorganize latent\n38\tknowledge already present in pretrained representations. Under this view, apparent SFT superiority can reflect elicitation\n39\tmatch, meaning that a recipe more reliably activates the checkpoint’s usable capacity rather than increasing the capacity it-\n40\t\n41\tself. Different SFT configurations impose different elicitation\n42\tbiases, which may match some pretrained instances better than\n43\tothers, leading to differences in activation reliability. Consequently, two SFT methods can exhibit ranking discrepancies\n44\tacross checkpoints: Method A may outperform Method B on\n45\tone pretrained instance, while Method B surpasses Method A\n46\ton another. Such discrepancies challenge the external validity\n47\tof conclusions drawn from single-checkpoint comparisons.\n48\tTo study this effect, we conduct a large-scale empirical investigation of SFT behavior in downstream speech classification. We evaluate eight SFT configurations along two axes:\n49\twhich intermediate representations are used for supervision,\n50\tand how much of the pretrained network is frozen during adaptation. These configurations are applied to nine widely used\n51\tself-supervised checkpoints from wav2vec 2.0, HuBERT, and\n52\tWavLM. Experiments are conducted on three SUPERB classification tasks [14]: intent classification (IC) [15, 16], emotion recognition (ER) [17, 18], and speaker identification (SID)\n53\t[19, 20]. To characterize run-to-run variability, we further repeat experiments with multiple random seeds on representative\n54\tbase-scale checkpoints.\n55\tOur results show that SFT comparisons can depend on the\n56\tspecific pretrained instance. Across tasks, switching checkpoints can change the relative ordering of SFT methods, including cases where architecture and model size are identical\n57\tand only the pretraining data differs. Multi-seed repetitions further reveal bidirectional transitions between fully activated and\n58\tunder-activated outcomes for the same checkpoint and configuration, which can both expose and mask row-wise top-group\n59\tdifferences. Overall, these findings suggest that reported improvements from SFT variants should be interpreted with caution: observed gains may reflect instance- and seed-dependent\n60\tactivation behavior, rather than a universally higher attainable\n61\tperformance ceiling.\n62\t\n63\tThis workmakes two contributions.\n64\t• We provide systematic empirical evidence that the identity\n65\tof the best-performing (or top-group) SFT configuration can\n66\tvary across pretrained instances, even when the backbone architecture and the model size are fixed.\n67\t• We introduce the perspective of elicitation match to interpret\n68\tapparent SFT superiority as differences in activation reliability across pretrained instances, explaining why top-group\n69\tresults on a single checkpoint may not transfer consistently.\n70\t\n71\t\fTable 1: Pretrained SSL checkpoints used in our study, with model size and pretraining data.\n72\tCheckpoint\n73\tFamily\n74\t#Params (M) Pretraining data\n75\tfacebook/wav2vec2-base-960h\n76\twav2vec 2.0\n77\t95.00\n78\tLibriSpeech 960h\n79\tfacebook/wav2vec2-base-100k-voxpopuli wav2vec 2.0\n80\t95.00\n81\tVoxPopuli (100k unlabeled subset)\n82\tfacebook/wav2vec2-large-960h\n83\twav2vec 2.0\n84\t317.00\n85\tLibriSpeech 960h\n86\tfacebook/wav2vec2-large-100k-voxpopuli wav2vec 2.0\n87\t317.00\n88\tVoxPopuli (100k unlabeled subset)\n89\tfacebook/hubert-base-ls960\n90\tHuBERT\n91\t95.00\n92\tLibriSpeech 960h\n93\tfacebook/hubert-large-ll60k\n94\tHuBERT\n95\t317.00\n96\tLibri-Light 60k\n97\tmicrosoft/wavlm-base\n98\tWavLM\n99\t94.70\n100\tLibriSpeech 960h\n101\tmicrosoft/wavlm-base-plus\n102\tWavLM\n103\t94.70\n104\tLibri-Light 60k + GigaSpeech 10k + VoxPopuli 24k\n105\tmicrosoft/wavlm-large\n106\tWavLM\n107\t316.62\n108\tLibri-Light 60k + GigaSpeech 10k + VoxPopuli 24k\n109\t\n110\t2. Problem Setup\n111\t\n112\t3.2. Backbones\n113\t\n114\t2.1. Problem Statement\n115\tWe study pretraining-dependent instability in choosing the top\n116\tSFT configuration for downstream classification: swapping the\n117\tpretrained SSL checkpoint (within the same backbone family\n118\tand scale) can change which SFT configuration is best, or statistically indistinguishable from the best, with all other settings\n119\tfixed.\n120\t2.2. Formal Setup\n121\tLet M be a pretrained SSL checkpoint, T a downstream task,\n122\tand s a random seed. Each SFT configuration a ∈ A yields\n123\ty = f (a, M, T, s),\n124\t\n125\t(1)\n126\t\n127\twhere y is the task metric reported by the evaluator.\n128\t2.3. SFT Configuration Space\n129\tWe parameterize configurations by FEATURE MODE mf ∈\n130\t{1, 2, 3} and FREEZE MODE mz ∈ {0, 1, 2}, denoted a =\n131\t(mf , mz ). We evaluate\n132\tA = {(1, 0), (1, 1), (1, 2), (2, 0), (2, 1), (2, 2), (3, 0), (3, 1)}.\n133\t2.4. Top-Group Instability Across Checkpoints\n134\tFor fixed (M, T, s), let\n135\t\n136\ta⋆ = arg max f (a, M, T, s).\n137\t\n138\t(2)\n139\t\n140\ta∈A\n141\t\n142\tDefine the top group as configurations not significantly worse\n143\tthan a⋆ under the paired exact McNemar test at level α:\n144\tG(M, T, s; α) = {a ∈ A : a ⊁ a⋆ at level α}.\n145\t\n146\t(3)\n147\t\n148\tWe can suspect top-group instability occurs between checkpoints M and M ′ if\n149\tG(M, T, s; α) ̸= G(M ′ , T, s; α).\n150\t\n151\t3.3. Configurations\n152\tEight SFT configurations are defined by FEATURE MODE∈\n153\t{1, 2, 3} and FREEZE MODE∈ {0, 1, 2}.\n154\tEach configuration is denoted as F mf -Zmz (e.g., F 1-Z2 denotes\n155\tFEATURE MODE=1 and FREEZE MODE=2).\n156\tFeature modes. FEATURE MODE=1 uses the final-layer\n157\tlast hidden state as the supervised representation.\n158\tFEATURE MODE=2 uses a single selected intermediate layer;\n159\twe fix the selected layer to the fourth layer from the end, i.e.,\n160\tℓ⋆ = L − 3. FEATURE MODE=3 uses a weighted-sum fusion\n161\tover transformer layers as the supervised representation.\n162\tFreeze modes. FREEZE MODE=0 fine-tunes the entire pretrained network together with the task head. FREEZE MODE=1\n163\tfreezes only the convolutional front-end and fine-tunes all transformer layers plus the task head. FREEZE MODE=2 freezes the\n164\tconvolutional front-end and the first N transformer layers, finetuning the rest and the task head (N = 4 in all runs).\n165\t3.4. Training Setup\n166\t\n167\ty ⋆ (M, T, s) = max f (a, M, T, s),\n168\ta∈A\n169\t\n170\tWe consider nine widely used self-supervised speech checkpoints spanning three model families: wav2vec 2.0, HuBERT,\n171\tand WavLM. Table 1 summarizes each checkpoint, including\n172\tparameter count and pretraining data. The table includes samearchitecture checkpoints pretrained on different data to enable\n173\tcontrolled analysis of pretraining-instance dependence.\n174\t\n175\t(4)\n176\t\n177\t3. Experiments\n178\t3.1. Datasets\n179\tWe evaluate downstream speech classification on three tasks\n180\tfrom the SUPERB benchmark: intent classification (IC), emotion recognition (ER), and speaker identification (SID). We follow the official SUPERB data splits and evaluation protocols\n181\tfor each task. Unless otherwise stated, we use the default evaluation metrics specified by SUPERB for the corresponding task.\n182\t\n183\tOur training recipe follows the official SUPERB downstream\n184\tconfigurations for IC, ER, and SID as closely as possible. All\n185\tdownstream fine-tuning and evaluation use the official SUPERB\n186\ttraining pipeline and built-in evaluator, with identical scripts\n187\tacross runs; only the pretrained checkpoint and random seed\n188\tare varied. For each task, we keep the entire pipeline fixed\n189\tacross all SSL checkpoints and SFT configurations, including\n190\tdata preprocessing, batching, and validation-based checkpoint\n191\tselection. Task-specific hyperparameters (optimizer, learningrate schedule, batch size, and training duration) are taken directly from the corresponding SUPERB configuration files and\n192\theld constant within each task. Each experiment is run on a\n193\tsingle NVIDIA H20 GPU, totaling approximately 10,000 GPUhours across all runs.\n194\t3.5. Seed Protocol\n195\tWe use a two-level seed design. For the full experimental matrix covering all nine SSL checkpoints, we run each\n196\t(checkpoint, task, SFT configuration) setting with a fixed default seed of 1337. To characterize run-level stochasticity,\n197\twe additionally perform multi-seed repetitions on three rep-\n198\t\n199\t\fTable 2: Test accuracy computed from paired prediction and truth files for all experiments with seed 1337. Values are bold when they\n200\tare not significantly different from the row maximum under a two-sided exact McNemar test at 95% confidence (alpha=0.05); small\n201\tvalues are marked as convergence anomalies with an asterisk (*).\n202\tTask\n203\t\n204\tModel\n205\t\n206\tF 1-Z0\n207\t\n208\tF 1-Z1\n20