tmicrosoft/wavlm-base. For these three checkpoints, we\n501\trepeat every (task, SFT configuration) setting with two extra\n502\tseeds, 2048 and 7395, resulting in three seeds in total (1337,\n503\t2048, 7395) for each of the corresponding runs.\n504\t3.6. Evaluation Outputs and Analysis Targets\n505\tFor each run, we report the task-defined metric using the official\n506\tSUPERB evaluation scripts. The experimental matrix produces\n507\tscores indexed by (checkpoint, task, SFT configuration, seed).\n508\tAll result aggregation, top-group identification via paired exact McNemar tests, and checkpoint- and seed-sensitivity analyses (including under-activation and pairwise sign flips) are presented in Section 4.\n509\t\n510\t4. Results\n511\tEach row in Tables 2 and 3 corresponds to a fixed downstream\n512\ttask and a fixed pretrained checkpoint, under which we compare\n513\tthe eight SFT configurations in Section 3. We mark systems that\n514\tare not significantly worse than the row-wise best as the top\n515\tgroup, i.e., statistically indistinguishable from the best under\n516\tthe paired exact McNemar test [21] at α = 0.05.\n517\t\n518\t4.1. Why the differences are not ceiling improvements\n519\tAt a glance, bold entries are not uniformly distributed across\n520\tcolumns, and some SFT configurations enter the top group more\n521\tfrequently across pretrained checkpoints. A naive interpretation\n522\tis that these configurations have an intrinsically higher attainable performance ceiling. However, several observations are\n523\tinconsistent with a ceiling-improvement explanation.\n524\tFirst, configurations that frequently enter the top group can\n525\tstill exhibit under-activation on certain checkpoints, producing\n526\tabnormally low performance on the same task. If the advantage primarily came from a systematically higher ceiling, one\n527\twould expect the relative ordering to be more consistent and the\n528\t“best” configurations to rarely collapse. Instead, extreme failures among apparent winners indicate that the observed gaps\n529\tare not simply explained by different upper bounds.\n530\tSecond, Table 3 shows that the effect is, to some extent,\n531\tseed-dependent and bidirectional. For the same task, pretrained\n532\tcheckpoint, and SFT configuration, changing only the seed can\n533\toccasionally turn an under-activated run into a fully activated\n534\tone that reaches the row-wise top group statistically indistinguishable from the best. Conversely, a configuration that is in\n535\tthe top group under one seed can become under-activated (or\n536\tmarkedly degraded) under another seed, without changing data,\n537\thyperparameters, or training mode. Such bidirectional transitions are difficult to reconcile with a stable ceiling-improvement\n538\tstory, but are consistent with sensitivity to the optimization tra-\n539\t\n540\t\fTable 3: Test accuracy computed from paired prediction and truth files for experiments with seeds 2048 and 7395, plus seed 1337\n541\tfor hubert-base-ls960, wav2vec2-base-960h, and wavlm-base, ordered to match the seed-1337 task and model layout. Values are bold\n542\twhen they are not significantly different from the row maximum under a two-sided exact McNemar test at 95% confidence (alpha=0.05);\n543\tsmall values are marked as convergence anomalies with an asterisk (*).\n544\tTask\n545\t\n546\tModel\n547\t\n548\tSeed\n549\t\n550\tF 1-Z0\n551\t\n552\tF 1-Z1\n553\t\n554\tF 1-Z2\n555\t\n556\tF 2-Z0\n557\t\n558\tF 2-Z1\n559\t\n560\tF 2-Z2\n561\t\n562\tF 3-Z0\n563\t\n564\tF 3-Z1\n565\t\n566\twav2vec2-base-960h\n567\t\n568\t1337\n569\t2048\n570\t7395\n571\t1337\n572\t2048\n573\t7395\n574\t1337\n575\t2048\n576\t7395\n577\t\n578\t0.6590\n579\t0.6839\n580\t0.6722\n581\t0.6834\n582\t0.6759\n583\t0.6798\n584\t0.1139*\n585\t0.1608*\n586\t0.1345*\n587\t\n588\t0.7057\n589\t0.7292\n590\t0.7061\n591\t0.7335\n592\t0.6947\n593\t0.7237\n594\t0.1977*\n595\t0.2880*\n596\t0.2082*\n597\t\n598\t0.7833\n599\t0.7838\n